text.tspan: Incoming network requests are blocked by default

flowRoot.flowPara: Zones restrict allowed services to an interface or network subset.
Active Zones show the zones which have been bound to an interface and/or network address.

As firewalling is complex, zones need to be explained a bit. There's a info icon next to the heading with a tooltip with a very simple explanation, with text (subject to change), similar to the following:
The top-level action is the remove button. Additional actions are in an overflow menu. At this time, the only additional action is "Set as default". (More will come later.)
The services list stays mainly the same. The notable change is the addition of the "Zone" column, which shows where the Service is allowed. Services may apply to multiple zones.
Read-only services have a special background and are not editable. When expanded, the service details would explain why the row is not editable.
Cockpit is read-only as removing it would break the ability to use Cockpit.
Services brought in by a zone are read-only and the notice (when expanded) would suggest removing the zone to remove the service.
Sorted from least trust to most trust
For use on internal networks. You mostly trust the other computers on the networks to not harm your computer. Only selected incoming connections are accepted.
Comma-separated ports, ranges, and aliases are accepted
Zones are shown sorted by trust level. There are two groups, each in thier own <fieldset>:
1. A filtered list of default zones, ordered from least trusted to most trusted.
2. Additional zones, provided by other system packages
Note: Don't worry about the styling of the radio groups. We'll handle that in the PR. The layout and styling (background line) are mainly CSS.

Adding a zone binds an existing zone to an interface and/or address range. The address range can be a comma separated list, dashed range (ex.: 0.0.0.0 - 255.255.255.255), or a subnet (ex.: 192.168.1.1/24), or a mix (separated by commas).
Description, Masquerade, and Included Services are <output>s showing how the service is enabled.
Interface and Allowed Addresses can be bound to any network interface and/or set of addresses.
When a network interface is selected, its address shows up. This helps to confirm it is the intended interface and helps when entering a range.
Sorted from least trust to most trust
For use on external networks. You do not trust the other computers on networks to not harm your computer. Only selected incoming connections are accepted.

When there is more than one zone, a zone selector shows up at the bottom of both services and ports selections. It is inline in both forms, and it ideally is in sync, in the rare case where someone starts to configure a service or a port and switches (to a port or service, respectively).
It's inline for better alignment and makes more sense this way conceptually. (Apologies for the extra code.)
When there is only one zone (as the Firewall page is by default), there is no zone selector. The default zone will be selected behind the scenes by default.
